segments.text: We had a large number of vets, but they were all in individual companies.
We had the Army, the Air Force, and we did not have a Marine Corps unit, but we had Army and Air Force both, and I don't think we even had Navy units at that time.
But I was on the
battalion staff and then became battalion commander in my senior year.
It was one of the battalions in the wing.
All right.
Compared to all the other
ordinary Corps outfits.
What was different about the way y'all got fish and sophomores and all?
We didn't have, we didn't have any great deal of distinction.
Once you got off the brave ground, went back to the dorms, you were all just the same.
So y'all didn't have any paddles?
No.
And no, no freshmen came to take care of your room?
No.
No, you were back,
Because that was, you know, that was sort of what we didn't want.
And you were older than average, that outfit was.
Yeah.
Now, where were you quartered then?
Over in the regular Corps area, what you call the quad now, I think.
Did you all march into the dining hall?
Marched in, we did everything the Corps did.
And we were just another unit in the Corps at that time, and had our own flags, our own
companies, the battalions and the wing and it wasn't that very well.
I mean, it was we it was like you're living two lives.
You got on the dress and formed a company you were military.
When you got back, you were just there's no distinction of what you had on the shoulder didn't make didn't make any difference.
You're all the same.

For you veterans, were there ever any special events, I'm trying to search for words here, where you as a former enlisted man and a former officer, did that ever matter after the war here on the campus?
No.
I had, in fact, one of the other fellows, and I should have mentioned while I was doing this,
was a marine lieutenant with me in China and all the time I was there.
He was my next officer, first officer.
He was a lieutenant.
I guess he finally made first lieutenant.
His name was Howard Whitney and I came back to A&M after I got out

when I came back to work here over visiting the department and there was Howard Whitney there and I'd served you know nearly a year with him in China but he was another very good member of the department and very useful and helpful and I think he went to he left here and went to I believe the University of Minnesota
And this arrangement within the Corps for the special veterans' outfits worked well?
As far as I could tell, it worked very well.
I never heard of any problems we created.
The commandant of the Corps at that time was General Boatner.
Describe him and his leadership style.
He was a tough cookie.

The only chewing out I ever got from a from a general who who had good reason to do so I was a battalion exec at the time and we were in a drill out on the main drill field I don't know which one I'd forgotten which one it was but I always had a chewing gum had a heavy chewing gum and I happened to have some in my mouth I knew better but uh
When we walked by, he saw it and invited me into his office the next day.
And along with, at that time, our battalion commander, whose name was Smith or Smythe, and he chewed both of us out.
Chewed me out for chewing gum, and I'd known better.
I'd been in the Marine Corps for nearly three years, and I knew you weren't supposed to do that.
I knew you weren't supposed to do that, according to him, and I did.
And then he got ahold of Smythe because he was my superior officer, and let him have it for a while.
Now, I've not heard anybody describe Boatner physically.
As I recall, he was not an imposing figure.
He was average height, or maybe not quite average height.
He was a little heavier than, wasn't quite as trim as some would like to be.
But he had a definite military bearing, and in a lot of ways, the demeanor
No, it wasn't.
I was gonna say he was like Earl Rudder, but he wasn't like Earl Rudder in his relationships to people, but he was, there was no question who was in the boss.
Now, when he was, uh, chewing you out, was he loud?
Yeah, he was pretty loud.
He'd get loud?
Okay.
He'd, uh, he got quite impressive.
Strong language?
bad language, but he, I think he was fully capable of doing that.
All right, would, if something happened during, out on the drill field or anything, did he ever yell at people?
Not that I recall.
He may have yelled at some of his officers.
But it was clear, clear who was in charge?
Yeah, it was.
He was, I think he went to put down that revolt in
And everybody I've talked to said they were not surprised.
No.
All right.
Did you have a car?
When did you get a car?
I got a car about four months after I got married in 1950.
Oh, okay.
None of the times I've been here.
I never could afford a car.
Uh, the, uh, so you weren't involved in, in much of anything off campus.
No.
Uh, and, uh, did you, did you and your friends attend any religious services while you were students?
Occasionally, not, not, uh, diligently, not, not every Sunday you went to church, but, uh, on occasion we would go to church.

was he went to different ones okay and they were all at the north gate or south side yeah they're all in both these areas did you by by chance know mr cashin i did not know him well i had seen him but i didn't really know him i knew who he was and knew what he was doing you know when here now jim would have been just about a classmate of yours he would have been i think he was a year ahead of me okay uh
Now, Red and I officiated football together for many, many years.
But you didn't know him?
I didn't know him then.
Jim, of course, was playing football.
And Red, I think, started then to play football, but never did go very far with it.
Let's see, here's an almost superfluous.
Did you and your buddies know about steam tunnels?
No.
I don't know where, in fact, I never did know really much about steam tunnels.
I still don't.
I know that they're here.
Do you know, did you know, do you know anything you can share about secret fraternities?
No.
No, and that's not because I'd
Wouldn't share it if I did, but I just don't know.
I have heard that there were secret fraternities, but I don't know of any.
There's one that apparently goes all the way back at least to Mr. Evans' time.
Is that right?
The swastikas, and their symbol was the novel, and they were using that a heck of a long time before Adolf Hitler was.
And as far as I can learn,
Now, I'm drawing the conclusion here, so it may be an error.
They were the TTs, the true Texans.

And I don't know whether they were anymore or not, but apparently the purpose of each of them, and the only purpose, was to get their members in the key core leadership positions, to have our guys in charge.
That was it.
Nothing ulterior, nothing... What were the major, for you and your acquaintances, what were the major...

uh indulgences smoking and drinking and so forth of course you learned to smoke as soon as you got in the service if you didn't smoke before you got in you did eventually soon then but that was it uh smoking you're drinking beer smoking uh what kind of cigarettes well uh what was the favorite brands the the big brands that time were camels and lucky strike which had come back from the war by that time
Cigars?
Not many cigar smokers.
Pipe smokers.
I smoked a pipe for many, many years.
And that was supposed to be intellectual, wasn't it?
Oh, yeah.
Well, I waited until I got intellectual before I started smoking a pipe.
Were there any Aggies that rolled their own much?
Quite a few.
Well, most of us out in the... Again, this is country ball.
You grew up.
You smoked out there.
You rolled your own.
But once you got here...
Did country boys continue to do that?
Poor ones did.
It costs much more to buy the ready rolls.
Did Aggies chew tobacco or dip snuff?
Not like they do now.
I think there's more of it now.
It sure seems to me to be than there was back when I was going to school.
Then in alcohol, beer, what favorite varieties?
You had Pearl and Southern Select and
Grand Prize.
Grand Prize.
Is that the one out of Louisiana?
There was one that came out of Louisiana?
Falstaff.
Falstaff, yeah.
That was the other one.
That was about it.
Then they had slits.
But Pearl was the one that I'd say at least the one I knew was the primary.
If somebody drank a mixed drink, what was it likely to be?
A salty dog was a...
because it was something you could just sort of put the gin and a little ice.
And if somebody poured something into a Coke bottle, what did they add?
Probably a bourbon if you put it in a Coke bottle.
It was probably a cheap bourbon that you could find.
Did any of you even know, had you ever seen marijuana?
You know, I still have never seen marijuana that I know of.
Did you all even know the word?
No.
Didn't know there was such thing.
And cocaine.
Cocaine.
Never heard of that.
I'm not much younger than you, but a little.
And the first time I ever heard of any of that was this two-bit movie of marijuana, and I can't remember what it was called, but supposedly if you smoked it, it made you completely insane.
And that was it.
And it was a dreary, dreary...
I don't think I have ever...
seen or been anywhere where marijuana was smoked during that time or really not since then.

What I do remember is that when you'd have a penny ante poker game, everybody that could afford them got a twofer cigar, lit it up, and the smoke was so thick in there that you could hardly see the cards.
Now, would Joel ever do that in a dorm room?
You do it in the dorm.
So smoking was allowed in the dorm.
Whiskey Bridge was in high gear then.
Did anybody ever get gypped at Whiskey Bridge?
I've never heard of any mention of that.
Not that I know of.
It was always afforded.
How common was it when you veterans were in the dormitory, how common was it for somebody to bring alcohol into the dorm?
Very uncommon.
We never did it.
I never knew anybody that did it.
As far as you know, were y'all inspected the same way the non-veteran corps members were in the dorm room?
No.
They didn't inspect?
No.
But y'all went out wearing the uniforms for the reviews and all that.
We wore uniforms every day.
Yeah, yeah.
And was there anything on your uniform that indicated you were a veteran?
No, unless you wore your ribbons.
How common was that?
Pretty common.
In all parades, we were supposed to wear all of our ribbons.
Were there some people, here's a serious question, were there some people in the Corps then that had earned some high decorations for bravery?
Silver Star.
Okay.
Yeah, that's number three.
No Distinguished Service Cross or Congressional Medal.
No, not that I recall.
All right, and he, had he already graduated?
Okay.
He had a lot of medals, well,
Good conduct and then your theater ribbons.
Congressional unit citations and that sort of thing.
Did you Pacific veterans ever tease the European veterans that y'all had done more than they had?
No, they were a bunch of candies up over there.
They didn't have to slog through all those jungles and do that sort of thing.
No, it was always a lot of talk back and forth about who really won the war and which one was the bad war to win.
I had a serious question here.
Compare the way the typical veteran who served in the Pacific
felt then and has continued to feel about his former enemy compared to the way the European theater veteran felt and feels about his enemy.
I think that those of us that fought the Japanese in the Pacific will never get over it.
I don't think the same feeling

really holds for the european group i mean maybe it's because they fought a whole bunch of different you know a whole bunch of different countries and not the same i don't know what it was but uh we uh we developed a very healthy dislike for the japanese uh i agree with your i have that summation i agree with do you do why uh

I don't know, maybe it was because, really starting with Pearl Harbor, the fact that they got the reputation of being a sneaky bunch of stabbers in the back that came in out of nowhere and started the whole conflagration, and it was up to us then to go try to bring it back again.
One day I was challenged by a young Japanese-American
about how awful, awful, awful we were to drop that bomb, and I responded with this question.
Do you think if the Japanese leadership of that era had had that bomb that they would have dropped it on us?
The conversation ended then.
Well, I thought then, and I still think now, that that was
the best solution that could have come at that time.
Saved lives.
It saved not only ours, but theirs as well.
If we had, if we really, and we were in the process, as I told you to begin with, loading up in Guam to go into Japan,
And had we gone in, it was going to be a bloodbath on both sides.
Well, I look what little I know about Iwo Jima and Okinawa.
It seemed to me the closer the American troops got to the mainland of Japan, the harder the Japanese got.
And the higher the losses, the more suicidal attacks and so forth.
Did you all spend much time, you veterans, spend much time talking about the war in your student days?
Did you all?
Not a whole lot.
You didn't replay much, did you?
We didn't replay it much.
We were just, I think most of us, just sort of glad it was over with and glad to get on.
Did you sometimes tease each other about which branch of the service had really done the...
Even in the Marine Corps, which boot camp did you go to?
Oh.
If you went to one of those candy...
places of Paris Island that didn't amount to that.
If you didn't go to San Diego and go through that, that's what we thought.
But that was, you know, it's always just like schools, I'm sure.
All right, give some examples of how did your Aggie pride and feelings, how did they get deeper during these student days?
Well, it was in some ways, I think,
at least as far as my experience is concerned, it was sort of a follow on to my experiences in the Marine Corps.
By the time I had finished boot camp in the Marine Corps, I was convinced we were the toughest rascals in the world and that there was nobody can stand up to us.
It sort of felt the same way come day in and day out.
We were
not the most prestigious place in the world, but we had the spirit, we were the good guys.
And it was something that after a while, you sort of get to where you're defending the flag against anyone who wants to mistreat you or say anything derogatory about A&M.
And it sort of builds on that.
And it lasts a long time.
I need to take a break.
Yeah.
How did your Aggie loyalties and fondness and commitment and debt, how did that begin to develop?
I think it's, well, one of the things I think is that you develop
an esprit de corps because of some of the hardships you go through that sort of bonds you to not only the other individuals but to the organization.

I've always felt that one of the luckiest things that I've been had happen to me is go to a poor little country school where you didn't really have a whole lot to go into the Marine Corps which was considered to be the
you've got what was left over from the Navy and nobody paid that, you know, they didn't really have appropriations in your equipment and all that sort of thing.
So you did the best you could with what you had.
And to a certain extent, it started that way with A&M.
So that I think was sort of what helped to develop the esprit de corps that I've had with A&M and that I think many others have had
that this is a tough place.
And did you realize that was developing while you were an undergraduate here?
Probably not.
Probably not.
I just, you know, it happened in retrospect.
I was just sort of thinking about the good consequences that come from what you consider at the time to be sort of hard times.
It's good for you.
Those two years in the Corps.
So you went to Silver Taps then.
Oh, yes.
Do you remember Muster as an undergraduate?
Not much.
I know I did go to Muster my senior year.
I do recall that.
But I think that's about the only one that I went to while I was an undergraduate.
And where was it held?
Do you remember?
Steps of the MSC?
Or what?
No, it wasn't finished yet.
The MSC wasn't finished until 50.
I think it was Gine Hall.
Okay.
Okay.
At that time.
What about Final Review, your senior year?
Well, Final Review was a big deal.
Describe that.
What made it a big deal?
Well, of course, that was the changing of the guard, as it were, of the juniors getting to become seniors.
And the senior year, as I said, having the...
turn over your responsibilities in the wing to your next one that was coming up was very impressive.
It was a very moving experience for me to find a review.
How did you feel that previous year when you put on those boots for the first time officially?
I thought that that was probably a great time of my life to be able to
finally get to wear a pair of senior boots, and be a member of the leading class at Texas A&M for the next year.
How much did they cost, do you remember?
Well, of course, I bought mine secondhand.
Sold them again when I got through.
Remember what you paid for them?
I think I paid $52 for them.
And they fit reasonably well?
Reasonably well.
I went on a trip one time with my roommate.
He and I decided on Friday afternoon that we were going to see, he knew a couple of girls up, and he was from Monroe, Louisiana.
And he had a girlfriend up right across the line in Arkansas.
So we were going up to visit.
We didn't take anything but boots and boot pants, and that was the most miserable weekend I've ever spent.
Old wool pants and hot and steamy and old boots.
I was glad to get home and get to take those off.
No, but they were a visible mark of you've gotten somewhere.
And that ring, how special was that?
Very special, still is, even though I've shrunk down now to where I have to wrap it with tape to keep it on my finger, but I've worn it continuously ever since then.
Do you remember what it cost?
Exactly.
I think, again, it was in the range of between, I think in the $45 to $50 range, which was a lot of money.
Of course, it's not the only thing we bought for my grandson's ring, and I think it was $375 or something like that.
Do you have any ring stories to tell?
You lost it or somebody spotted that ring on your finger?
That happens to me all the time, particularly, I think, because it's worn down so much.
And the ones that I get that I always want to come up to are the new graduates, the ones that have gotten their ring in the last year or two.
They say, is mine going to look like that one of these days?
What did you do to get it all worn down like that?
Well, I just kept it on my finger all the time.
Have you ever had it spotted somewhere on the other side of the world?
Yes.
in Africa.
We were down in Nairobi and of all places.
Of course they got bars everywhere.
We were in a bar and I happened to have my hand up on that and the guy sitting next to me said, that sure looks like an Aggie ring.
And of course he had one too.
He had lived there for several years and of course I guess that was the first one he'd seen in a while.
All right, Aggie, at your final, final review, who came that was special?
Well, my family, my mother and dad, did not really travel a whole lot.
We were country folks and didn't go, and they did not come, but I had, oh, let's see, I had one of my brothers, two of my brothers were here.
for a final review, and their family.
So it was a... And then commencement was held where?
Outdoors?
I think it was outdoors.
I really do.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
No.
Wasn't that year with Eisenhower?
I don't think so.
And what kind of,
What kind of world did you think you were going out into?
If you recall, 1950 was not a good year.
Jobs were hard to find.
Even graduate positions, graduate school student positions were getting hard to find, you know, assistantships and fellowships and so forth.
So I thought that, you know, I had better, I wanted to go ahead and go ahead and

finish up getting at least a master's degree and hopefully going to have a PhD sometime and say that opportunity to do that you know that field and I didn't I didn't have jobs waiting for me so I got an assistantship in the ag eco department and I was very happy to get that under John McNeely and that was for the fall of 1950 for the fall of that fall and I worked we developed the uh
a model livestock auction system where we got to travel all over the state and look at all the livestock auction sales and at that time 1950 was the time when
Cattle prices were very volatile, and we had people that were making a living by buying 500 head of cattle here and selling them over here the next day.
And they were wearing the cattle out, just moving them from one auction to the other.
And when did you learn you were going to get that assistantship?
How long before commencement?
Not until after commencement.
When I left, I didn't really have a job.
waiting for me.
I told him that he was looking into it, but then shortly after that, he said, you know, he had money for it.
You remember what the stipend was?
$125 a month.
But you, let's see, no, you'd used up your GI Bill.
Used up the GI Bill.
Yeah, yeah.
And so that began in the fall of 50.
Yeah.
Where were you, what did you think when you heard about the invasion of
of Korea by North Korea.

I began to wonder if I'd really made a mistake in going ahead and getting that commission because it looked like they were going to call up a bunch of us who had served less than four or five years in the military and was quite concerned.
And they did call up a number of people that I graduated with.
In fact, my roommate was called up.
He had served only a very brief time in the Air Force.
And he was called up for the Korean War.
Now, your commission was Army or Air Force?
Air Force.
Air Force.
But non-pilot.
I probably was the oldest second lieutenant ever in the Air Force.
I got my commission, went into the reserves, never went to a meeting or anything like that.
And so after about three years, they called me and said,
Are you really still on the books as a second?
We don't have second lieutenants that spend two or three years in rank.
We need to get you either active or get you discharged.
I said, well, obviously I'm not doing anything in here, so let's just go ahead and discharge.
All right, so summarize your, was it two years working on your master's as assistant?
No, it only took a year.
A year.
And by the time I was married, I got married between the time of finals and graduation.
All right, now I have this special...
